Multiple Sclerosis: It’s not just the drugs that matter, but the patient’s will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: a neurologist, physiotherapist, occupational therapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations, if they decide to have a child, social and legal counselling, recommendations for housing adjustment, etc.
Still, all this is not enough: the development of the disease can be fundamentally influenced by the patient himself.
The more actively he fights the disease, the longer he can work and does not have to fundamentally change the style of his life.
As doctors warn, the passivity of patients frees up space for disease activity.
For example, regular exercise has been shown to significantly delay the time when a patient needs a compensatory aid, such as a cane.
It is important that patients and their surroundings are not subject to various myths, for example, that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That’s why we created the website “Give Yourself a Chance” (www.bezmytu.cz), which is supported by the ongoing media campaign “Give Yourself a Chance”.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
For multiple sclerosis, there is a saying that the sooner the disease is treated, the more likely the doctor can influence something.
This is because we have drugs for multiple sclerosis in the inflammatory stage, when the process of neurodegeneration is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the hope that we will be able to stop the disease and delay disability, explains Dr. Eva Medová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
It is very important for people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often solves the weakening of the lower limbs or balance disorders.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, relieve swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It's really individual, it depends on the specific problems of the patient," says Dr. Martina Kovari, the head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine at the University Hospital in Motol.
Although people with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, it manifests itself in a slightly different way.
Rehabilitation cannot stop the disease, but it can always relieve its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the immune state of the body, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive aspect of regular exercise is the fact that patients check what they can do, and this strengthens their confidence.
"Exercise also flushes out endorphins and one feels good after it," warns Dr. Kamila Řasová from the Rehabilitation Medicine Clinic of the University Hospital in Vinohrady.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We directly interfere with the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"Previously, these patients were so-called sparing, today we know that they need a targeted burden," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic at the University Hospital in Motol.
The goal of physiotherapy is that a person can remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including work placement.
Physiotherapists therefore work with occupational therapists to provide each person with a tailor-made compensatory aid.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They are in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people are shocked.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
It must respond to a heavy load - the loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we are to go to someone, not to try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them so that they eventually come to the conclusion that even with a disability it is possible to live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
Without the Prague-based manufacturer Latecoere, airbuses would not fly.
Aviation production is synonymous with precision and advanced technologies.
New aircraft are full of titanium or light and solid composite materials, which no one can manufacture and process.
Yet, in addition to super-accurate, computer-controlled machine tools, in addition to autoclaves for shaping composites, you can come across something as common as apricot pits.
In the drum, which resembles a cotton candy pot, the edges of the sheet metal parts that have just come out of the milling machine are grinded in a pile of stones.
"So far, no one has found anything better," smiles Ivan Dubský, CEO of air door manufacturer Latecoere Czech Republic.
On the premises in Prague Letňany, Letov produces a complete door for the Airbus A320.
They are the only ones in the world to supply doors for the Brazilian Embraer 170.
The doors, part of which is assembled in Prague, also allow passengers to enter the first and upper class on the upper decks of the world’s largest Airbus A380 airliner.
There are also doors full of composites for the new Boeing 787 Dreamliner.
Accuracy is the main motto here.
For example, the moment keys are set by the company twice a year.
If there is no inspection record on the yellow sticker, they should explain at the Prague plant to auditors from Airbus or Boeing, who go regularly to check whether the doors are made according to the agreed rules.
However, advanced technology has not yet completely replaced the human senses.
There are 1500 rivets on one door to the A320.
These must be manually tapped by the riveters.
It takes them two days.
Even from the sound of the hammer hitting, they will know whether the rivet is already properly tapped.
The tolerance in which they operate is minimal.
The rivet can rise above the surface of the aircraft from zero to 0.13 millimeters.
That's about twice the thickness of a human hair.
During the check comes a trained touch.
When the controller runs his finger over a row of rivets, he will know if any is out of tolerance.
Then he picks up the exact dial.
Letov fed the program of the L-39 military trainer aircraft before 1989.
In 1991, not one was produced.
The company had to find new jobs quickly.
At that time, it was joined by the European aircraft manufacturer Airbus.
She won a tender for an emergency door supplier for the A321.
The Boeing deal wasn't that good.
"We were a small company for them at the time, which did not have enough money to invest and to guarantee Boeing long-term stable supplies," Dubský recalls.
The door to the American manufacturer would have remained closed if Letov had not attracted the French group Latecoere at the Prague conference of the international association of the aviation industry in 1999.
We talked about our relationship with Airbus.
The next day, negotiations with the French began, Dubský says.
A year later, Latecoere bought the Czech company and with a strong company came new orders.
In 2000, the assembly of door parts for the A320 began.
Three years later, the upper deck doors were added for the A380.
In 2006, the company built a new composite processing hall for deliveries to the Boeing Dreamliner.
Without Latecoere, we wouldn't be able to get to these big jobs on our own.
Maybe we'd do parts or small parts.
The partners want guarantees of supplies for twenty or thirty years, Dubský explains.
Last year, the Czech Latecoere achieved a turnover of over 2.9 billion and profit after tax of CZK 147 million.
Exclusive position among suppliers of aircraft manufacturers is not free.
Latecoere has invested CZK 1.5 billion in Prague since 2000.
The company must have quality certificates, certification of 170 specific production processes and certificates of qualification for key employees.
Without them, the company would not produce any doors to aircraft.
Obtaining certificates that production processes meet customer requirements and in repeated inspections cost millions of crowns.
Production processes change every year.
They are more accurate and strict.
We have to retrain our employees, re-equip the equipment and re-certify the whole process, adds Dubský.
Now the company is completing the process of zinc and nickel plating, which will replace the previously harmful cadmium for human health.
They got the assignments from the manufacturer, but then they had to adapt the technology for the equipment or chemicals they use in Prague.
People from Boeing will come, check the concept of the entire line.
Then we show them the production.
They'll check out our lab.
They will test one set of samples themselves in their laboratory and then compare the results with ours, describing Dubský’s way of controlling them.
The reward is long-term exclusive contracts for the Prague company.
With the Prague plant, the production of embraers is now standing and falling.
For the A320, it produces half of the total door volume.
Replacing the Czech Latecoere is either impossible or very difficult for a Brazilian or European manufacturer.
However, this does not mean that he could ask for any price at the door.
The contract includes a price curve.
It indicates how much one door will cost after ten, fifty, hundred pieces produced.
The price per piece keeps falling to a certain limit value.
We have to fit into this price formula.
If not, we will lose, Dubsky says.
Half of the hall, where the electrical cabinets for the Airbus A400 M military aircraft are assembled, is empty.
It is a symbol of the future.
Behind the screen, a new semi-robotic riveting and door assembly line is being built for the A320 Neo.
Riveting will speed up and refine.
"This is the trend that assembly in aviation is taking," adds Dubský.
The future line is secured.
Airbus has ordered 3,278 A320s so far.
Just a few meters away there will be a line for the complete installation of doors for the upper deck of the A380.
This is a strategic decision of our parent company.
The aim is to reduce production times and costs.
Full assembly could begin in two years, Dubský says.
Before that, however, the company must pass qualification tests, for example, for the installation of some electrical and electronic devices in the doors for the largest Airbus.
The company is also focused on the further development of composite materials production.
In addition to Boeing, it will also participate in the new Airbus A350 program, which will compete with the American Dreamliner.
"It is a huge credit for the company if it can process composites in addition to metal materials," says Dubský proudly.
Latecoere, however, is on the verge of production capacity in the Czech Republic.
There is no other place in the area of Letov where they are based.
Before the entry of the French mother, the company had 180 employees.
Now it has 800, and in three years it could be a hundred more.
As long as Airbus and Boeing are able to anticipate how many hundreds of new aircraft they order each year, they won’t have to worry about the job.
Despite having orders for several years in advance, the parent company of Prague’s Latecoere faced the threat of bankruptcy.
The French group did not have enough money for the September loan repayments.
In the end, Latecoere was able to reach an agreement with the main creditors.
At the end of August, they exchanged some of their loans for shares.
