Members supported a larger share of the state's coal levies.
The change in mineral mining fees is to bring CZK 427 million more to the state treasury than in 2013.
According to the government, the revenue of municipal budgets is to have a neutral impact, because the fee is to be higher.
In the previous year, municipalities received about CZK 450 million in fees and the state budget of CZK 150 million.
About 200 million crowns went to municipalities and 66 million crowns to the state from lignite mining.
The amendment also envisages increasing the payment from mining areas to CZK 1,000 per hectare per year.
The income from these payments will continue to belong to the municipalities in full.
The Minister of Industry Jan Mládek (ČSSD) told MPs that the municipalities would receive CZK 14 million to 100 million per year instead.
The amount of mining fees will no longer be determined by law, but by government decree.
The remuneration is newly calculated as the product of the amount of mineral extracted and the rate for individual types of minerals.
According to the government, the reason for the change is, among other things, the possibility of a flexible response to the current economic situation.
However, ODS MP Marek Benda warned that the setting of the fee may not be in line with the constitution.
However, according to Mládek, this is not a tax, because the state charges the mineral, which is state property.
Only municipalities whose territory is affected by mining receive fees.
In the case of deep coal mining, three-quarters of the money will go to the municipality and one-quarter to the state.
The same applies to the extraction of radioactive materials.
Part of the money that the state collects from mining fees will be earmarked.
For example, 28 percent will have to go to repair damage after mining or to provide mining rescue services.
The bill has been criticised by opposition MPs, who said it would harm mining communities and regions.
For example, Michal Kučera (TOP 09 and Mayors) warned that mining companies will no longer want to sponsor municipalities as before, because they will pay higher fees directly to the state budget.
