"Sonogenetics" or control of brain cells by sound waves
This video shows how sound impulses affect the direction in which the nematodes move.
Scientists have raised worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
Small nematodes change direction when they are hit by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
Pulses work by switching cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasound waves.
Related: Scientists Can Read and Record Brain Activity Using Light
The researchers said these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart and muscle cells and activates outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure that inserts electrodes into a patient’s brain that stimulate the brain.
The nematodes usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that the reaction occurs when they are placed in a fluid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he found, the bubbles amplify the ultrasonic waves, which then pass through the body of the worms.
Amplified ultrasonic waves act in the ion channels of TRP-4, which is found in the membranes of some worm cells.
With sound waves, these channels open and activate the cells with which they are connected, according to a report in the journal Nature Communications.
In order to control the nematodes using ultrasound waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contain TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by microbubbles and transferred to the worms, where they switched on the modified motor neurons.
The new method is in many ways similar to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light.
However, Chalasani said that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by optical fiber to the desired location in the brain, ultrasound waves can penetrate tissues without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
“We believe that by using gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to the ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases,” Chalasani said.
He added that the method could also be used in the treatment of muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
