Apple has a yo-yo effect.
It's all because of the displays.
A more powerful processor, a higher-resolution camera, a stronger chassis, and a touch-recognition display are, in short, the advantages of the recently introduced ninth-generation iPhones.
The latter two also have a negative impact on the size and weight of iPhone 6s and 6s Plus.
Apple’s current trend has been that each new generation of iPhone is lighter than the previous one.
The exception was the third and fourth generation, whose weight slightly increased compared to previous iPhones.
The two-gram difference in weight to the disadvantage of the novelty was really negligible.
However, this is not the case with the new iPhones.
Compared to last year's iPhone 6 and 6 Plus, the weight of the smaller model increased by 14 grams, and the larger one by 20 grams.
On the one hand, it is not surprising that last year's affair with bending in Apple's pockets greatly troubled.
The chassis is made of a more durable aluminum alloy 7000, which was also projected on the weight.
But the displays have a much greater impact on it.
Apple uses 3D Touch technology to recognize the power of touch.
To do this, the display had to be equipped with an additional layer of capacitive sensors.
Thus, the weight of the new iPhone displays has more than doubled compared to previous generations.
For a smaller iPhone, it was originally 12 grams to 29 grams, and for a larger iPhone, it was 19 to 40 grams.
For iPhone 6s, the display is the hardest component to use.
The weight of just 143 grams is also achieved thanks to the slimming crust, which touched most of the remaining components.
In the case of a larger model, it is the heaviest used element of the battery, but its weight has not changed compared to its predecessor.
Even in this case, the greatest increase is seen in the display.
The weight of the 5.5-inch iPhone 6s Plus is 192 grams.
As far as the new display technology is practical, it will only be visible during use.
The first users will be able to try it out on Friday, September 25, when sales of iPhone 6s and 6s Plus will start in selected countries.
Have the breakfast cereals been champions for tens of thousands of years?
In the Italian town of Grotta Paglici, archaeologists have managed to find something that opens up interesting possibilities.
They discovered traces of settlement by modern man from various times, including wall paintings, tool remnants, and so on and so forth.
In layer 23A, which according to the instruments is dated to about 30,000 years ago, scientists have discovered something that closely resembles the remains of a breakfast buffet.
Traces of oat grains were found on the site, which apparently went through the process of producing today’s popular flakes.
In this case, the grains are soaked first, then dried, stripped of the packaging, so-called rinses, then steamed and spread flat.
In the Paglicci cave, it was possible to discover grains that were apparently heated or scorched, and then apparently crushed between two millstones - at least this is indicated by the traces of use on two stones in the cave.
Thus, the scientists could not prove in their publication for the PNAS journal that the complete process of producing flakes was taking place in the cave, but the similarity is really very noticeable.
We also have no evidence of how people could eat flakes, but the assumption that it was with some liquid, and quite possibly warm, is, of course, offered quite logically.
At the same time, it is a very interesting proof of how intensively people used cereals long before the emergence of agriculture.
If the interpretation is correct, the oldest flakes have overtaken agriculture by about twenty thousand years.
