The symbol of the village came to life.
The wheel of the windmill over Chlum is spinning again after years.
It can be seen from afar, because it is located on a fifteen-meter-high mast.
People from all over the place call it the "windmill on Chlum".
For the village with 150 inhabitants, it even became one of the elements of the municipal emblem, which the village received on the occasion of the meeting of natives in 2010.
"We asked for a sign and of course we wanted to have a fan on the sign, everyone knows it in the vicinity," said Mayor Jiří Mašek.
The Chlum wind pump is a local technical monument.
It is also a memento of the present: it is reminiscent of the time when local people were fighting for quality drinking water.
The one in Chlum in past centuries was a rarity.
It was not until 1910 that the Chlum representatives decided for the solution, which was then suitable until the mid-1980s.
In the village near the branch to Číchov they had dug a seven-meter deep well.
Three years later, they completed the well with a metal structure with a wind pump, which pumped water into the reservoir at the highest point of the village, near the local church.
"The construction was carried out by Antonín Kunc from Hranice na Moravě at a cost of CZK 2,400," the memorial inscription on the ground-floor fence of the mast structure reads.
The pump, after several repairs and falls of the wind wheel, expired in 1971.
On 7 May 1973 a new chapter of the struggle for water began: on that day a new water supply began to serve in Chlum.
The wind pump remained only a dysfunctional municipal symbol and local rarity.
The dominance was put into operation at this year's gathering of natives.
It was not until 2008 that the Chlumští decided to repair the wind wheel again and put it back into operation.
They made a replica of the original wheel - reduced in diameter by half a meter.
The wheel was mounted on a mast, but the same year it had to be brought down.
The manufacturer of the replica did not choose the right material and the bike could not resist the gusts of wind.
After that, the Chlum dominant rested under the roof for several years.
Since June this year, however, the wheel on the high mast has been spinning again.
On the occasion of the meeting of natives, the village had the replica of the bike modified and re-installed it on the top of the iron tower.
But the wheel draws utility water from the well only to the overflow blind arm.
And over the summer, we completely unplugged it, because there was little water in the well.
At least it turned out empty.
"In the autumn, we will disconnect the windmill shaft from the pump in the suction basket again," the mayor explained.
Chlum is not the only village in the Czech Republic where the wind wheel has become a municipal emblem, but it is the only village of this kind in the entire Highlands.
They have a similar element in the emblem in honor of local technical monuments, for example in Chvalkovice and Zelená Hora in the Vyškov region, in Kuželov in the Hodonín region, Partutovice in the Přerov region or in the Police in the Vsetín region.
