At its most anticipated meeting in years, federal reserve lawmakers will spend two days this week seated at the 27-foot-long Honduran mahogany table, deciding whether it's time to raise the key interest rate after nearly a decade.
Towering above them at one end of the central bank ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the nation's economic interests above everything else.
The central bank has a double charge from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping local prices stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be an X-factor too close to the predictable decision to be announced on Thursday on whether the U.S. economy is ready to launch when weaning off an unprecedented stimulus in the form of a near-zero short-term interest rate on-site since late 2008.
Although most data shows solid economic growth, recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed by adding to volatility by raising its federal funds reference rate - no more than a mere quarter of a percentage point.
"It's clear that the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch in the first place," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to increase the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already provides them with sufficient justification to wait any longer," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is causing nervousness in the financial markets.
About half of economists recently polled by Blomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to delay the matter, with the key indicator only about a 30% chance of an increase.
This would point to a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises rates only if politicians soften the slump with the promise that further increases are not in sight.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industry average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers would hold rates quiet this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed raised rates now," he said.
If the Fed’s politicians did this, “they would have to go to the extreme in their program statement and hold hands with the financial markets so they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise its rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in the slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US economic recovery.
Yellen said that despite spring and early summer, she expects rates to rise this year despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labour market has seen solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of lifting.
And while inflation continues to run below the central bank’s annual 2% target, Fed policymakers say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness of the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to shake up late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below its record value in May, as investors worried that China’s slowing economy would drag down global growth.
The market rebounded somewhat this month, and the Dow is now only losing nearly 10% of its May high.
The Fed’s uneasy market situation provides a comprehensive calculation of when to start raising interest rates.
"In the absence of what has happened in the financial markets, and reports of the weakness of the Chinese economy over the past few weeks, there would have been tightening at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at UCLA's Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
He now predicts that they will wait at least a month to gain better control over the consequences.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about what impact this will have on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to rely on about the latest developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s main concerns, so technically it should not be included in their decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The central bank’s influence in recent years has been enormous.
The mere hint of then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could "pin" their monetary expansion in the market has triggered convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interconnected, Fed officials can be expected to follow developments elsewhere, but they also consult with other central bankers and experts to better read the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of Envestnet Inc's global wealth-management strategy.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that "the Fed has a history of excessive movements in financial markets that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting policy-making member of the Federal Open Market Committee who pushed for rate hikes, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage points over three sessions "despite limited identifiable impacts on US growth," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed these cuts.
The Fed should prioritize financial stability concerns only during a major crisis, such as the 2008 market meltdown, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the rate-setting committee at the Bank of England.
The latest turmoil is not even close to that level, he said.
"You certainly don't want to be in a situation of fear of rate increases because markets have become angry," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a double mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don’t think they should be on the cutting edge.
