For Slightly Obese Diabetics, Weight Loss Surgery Could Be Useful
The benefits of weight loss surgery for moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes may last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say whether moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those who are provided with non-surgical treatment.
"Mortality data takes a long time to show," says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote an editorial on a new study of JAMA surgery.
Surgery for weight loss, bariatric surgery use different methods to reduce the stomach.
Reduce hunger and limit the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective for treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the survey was conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the relationship of weight to height, is considered normal at values between 18.5 and 24.9.
BMI values of 25 or higher indicate an overweight person, and people with a value above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a 2007 study that looked at two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy - in the treatment of type 3 diabetes in people who were moderately obese.
The average BMI among those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who did not receive surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was completely resolved in 36 percent and partially in 28 cases.
In the treatment group, diabetes was completely resolved in only 1 percent and partially in only about 2 percent of patients.
In addition, control of blood pressure, triglycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol was shown to be "generally better in the surgical group," the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient’s levels of hemoglobin A1c in the blood, which reflects the body’s ongoing blood sugar levels.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7%, the researchers said.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the treated group, this value remained at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycemic control" -- which is reflected in better hemoglobin A1c levels -- did not reduce mortality at five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results with two types of operations.
After the fifth year, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1), and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 versus 2.1 percent), and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 versus 16.7 percent).
While the new study does not show an improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden where they found that surgery leads to life extension, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29 percent more likely to survive in the next 15 years, compared to the group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not show an improvement in survival among post-surgery patients, according to Blackstone, it is a reassuring result for people with BMI under 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"Right here, this work is critical because it states that surgery is safer in the lower BMI group," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone also argues that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously after a decrease in a patient’s BMI between 27 and 30.
"I think we've waited too long to show people the seriousness of the situation," he says.
