In the event of bankruptcy, the insurance companies are to cover the claims of the clients in full.
Insurance companies should cover the claims of clients in the event of the bankruptcy of the travel agency in full.
This was decided on Wednesday by the House when it approved an amended amendment to the Tourism Business Conditions Act.
Travel agencies will be able to replace bankruptcy insurance with a bank guarantee, according to the draft, which is to be assessed by the Senate.
Insurance companies do not agree with the obligation to pay their clients’ claims above the agreed limit.
The Ministry of Regional Development insists on the adjustment, arguing for consumer protection.
Insurance companies have already threatened to stop insuring travel agencies against the crash when the amendment comes into force.
Travel agencies have also criticised the proposal.
Without insurance, they will have to leave or go abroad.
Minister for Regional Development Karla Šlechtová (for ANO) pointed out that cases where insurance companies did not pay full compensation are not Eurocomform.
She drew attention to this year's decision of the Constitutional Court, which confirmed that the client is entitled to a full refund regardless of the insurance limit.
Insurance companies will receive enough information about the management of travel agencies and will be able to set the right limit, Šlechtová stressed.
"We appreciate the effort to increase consumer protection, but it must have such a limit that it is feasible," said Miroslav Kalousek, vice-president of TOP 09.
The bank guarantee will not work because no one will give it unlimited.
"Travel agencies will have to stop their activities or move abroad," Kalousek warned.
A member of the Presidium of the Association of Czech Travel Agencies Tomio Okamura (SPD) disagreed with Kalouska’s concerns on the basis of a survey among the CC members.
“Stop lobbying insurance companies,” he said.
Okamura does not consider the statements of the insurance companies to be relevant, there is no official written statement to this effect.
However, they are trying to find out whether the travel agencies will be complicit, which is not a problem, according to Okamura.
Jana Fischerová (ODS), who referred to the opinion of the rival Association of Travel Agencies of the Czech Republic, and her party colleague Petr Bendl, who spoke about erasing stairs for Czech travel agencies, also warned against the provision.
According to Fischer, travel agencies will not be able to negotiate insurance.
“Consumer protection works,” Fischer said.
Her motion to dismiss the disputed passage was not approved by the House.
Vojtěch Filip (KSČM) also failed with the proposal to return the draft to the committee due to the alleged violation of the Civil Code.
Filip pointed to travel agencies, which he said could be a threat to consumers.
The draftsman Martina Berdychová (ANO) withdrew her proposal, which would limit the liability of insurance companies in cases where they could not know that the insurance benefit would not cover the entire risk.
The amendment will not initially propose a minimum limit of four million for travel agencies offering air travel, and a limit of one million for offices selling, for example, bus tours.
The limit will remain at 30% of planned sales.
However, the limit of insurance payments will have to be such that in the event of the bankruptcy of the travel agency, it will cover all the claims of the customers.
Even after the modifications, the standard stipulates that travel agencies will have to indicate which travel agency organizes the tour for the sold tours.
Before concluding the contract, travel agencies will have to provide insurance companies with, among other things, data on management and number of trips.
The approved amendment of the Public Administration Committee also provides for further regular information to insurance companies.
Every month, travel agencies will have to provide them with data on the number of passengers and tours sold, the total price of tours sold, and the amount of advances and sales for tours and vouchers.
If the Ministry of Regional Development finds that the travel agency has not fulfilled any of the legal obligations towards the insurance company, it will call on it according to the draft to correct it or will be able to prohibit it from entering into new contracts in case the breach of the obligation could endanger the interests of customers.
The amendment is also to amend the financing of the mountain service.
The Ministry of Regional Development will determine the amount of the subsidy to the mountain service on the basis of its application, which will be submitted by the end of April for the next year.
The application will contain a report on the use of state money last year, a financial plan for expenditure and a outlook for the next two years.
According to the association, however, the legislator did not think about the situation, what will happen if the insurance company terminates the contract.
It will not be allowed to organize tours and clients who purchased the tour before the termination of insurance will lose it, according to the association.
In such a case, CK will suffer a significant loss and may even go bankrupt, even though its management was in good shape.
