Xi calls for opening up the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told the group, whose task is to reform governance on Tuesday.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies," he said regarding the 16th meeting of the central group to deepen the overall reform.
Promoting openings in nascent reforms will give new impetus and vitality, as well as provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The lead group has adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, a relaxation of the border control policy, support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital, and a reorganisation of the registration resident system.
The statement states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and businesses that are outside the investment limits.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through testing programs.
The move is significant because it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls on the powers it delegates to companies and make sure that companies themselves decide how to run their businesses.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be open to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of companies that are funded from abroad and will provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card," thanks to the optimization of requirements and simplification of the application process.
Ensuring the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
In the Karlovy Vary region, there may be new bed wards.
According to Jakub Pánik, Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region (ČSSD), the current capacity of the wards of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the wards of individual hospitals.
There are also opportunities to expand care.
For example, a one-day surgery center could be established in the surgical department, where according to the set concept, surgical procedures that do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours would be performed.
It is not yet clear in which specific hospitals the day-to-day surgery facilities should be.
At the skin department of the Karlovy Vary hospital, a laser center could be established with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the creation of an apalic center to care for patients with brain disabilities who are in a vegetative state.
Such a center should be established centrally and should be an integral part of the anesthesiology-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility in the Ostrov hospital, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity, which seems to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary region, are the beds of aftercare, in particular the beds of the Long-Term Sick Care Centre (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and above all should be closely linked to the acute care beds.
Part of this device should function as a rehabilitation bed and part as a classic LDN bed, recommended concept.
As he points out, aftercare beds are missing mainly in the Karlovy Vary hospital.
